;Many people hear the term Web literacy and think it means learning to code, or <abbr>STEM</abbr> (science, technology, engineering, math) education. But Web literacy is much broader than that – it should include all the skills to be confident and competent online. To be empowered digital citizens, we all need to know how to navigate, how to share, what information to trust, and most importantly, how to expand the frontiers of our knowledge.
K'ïy winaqi' nikak'axaj ri tzij Ajk'amaya'l choltz'ib'anem nikina'ojij chi richin netamäx nuk'unem, o <abbr>STEM</abbr> (etamab'alil, na'ob'alil, retamab'alil nojk'ay, ajilanem). Xa xe chi ri Ajk'amaya'l choltz'ib'anem nïm chuwäch ri' – k'o chi eruk'wan ronojel ri etamab'äl richin jikïl chuqa' taqel pa k'amab'ey. Richin tikirel nok jun kemtz'ib'il amaq'el, qonojel k'o chi niqetamaj achike rub'eyal yojok pa k'amaya'al, achike rub'eyal yojkomonin, achike etamab'äl ütz nikuqub'äx ak'u'x chi rij, chuqa' ri yalan k'o rejqalem, achike rub'eyal niqanimirisaj ruchi' qetamab'al.


